preferred_body.text:
This was originally aired way back on March 8, before the dangers of asymptomatic spread were clearly understood. Today he and other health care policy experts recommend wearing masks when in public in order to reduce the possibility of unknowingly spreading the virus to others. 

It is really important, especially as relates to the pandemic, to note the dates of news stories and when health recommendations were made and adjusted as more is learned about how COVID-19 behaves and how it is spread.

preferred_body.text: Personally, when I wear it. It is a constant reminder for me to not touch my face and to be mindful of being careful. What he is saying is all fine, but I think it has more to do with causing shortages for the front line workers that anything. If you can have the virus without symptoms you can spread it, even if you do show symptoms, you likely have been spreading it for days before showing first symptoms. Wearing a mask protects others from that. No ppe is perfect, but even if it does reduce the chance by whatever margin, it only makes sense. All ppe needs to be used properly to work properly. This is no different
